This paper is likely to belong to the sub-category of machine learning (cs.LG) as it focuses on improving the performance of few-shot learning algorithms through metric scaling and task conditioning. Additionally, the paper uses deep learning techniques and proposes an end-to-end optimization procedure based on auxiliary task co-training, which are common in the machine learning field. The paper also involves image classification tasks, which suggests that it could belong to the computer vision (cs.CV) sub-category. The use of task conditioning and metric scaling also suggests that the paper could belong to the artificial intelligence (cs.AI) sub-category. The paper also involves natural language processing tasks, which suggests that it could belong to the computational linguistics (cs.CL) sub-category. Finally, the use of deep neural networks and optimization procedures suggests that the paper could belong to the neural and evolutionary computing (cs.NE) sub-category.
